On December 31, 2019, the pneumonia cluster with unknown etyology was reported in Wuhan, Hubei Province, China.
On January 9, 2020, China’s Center for Disease Control and Prevention reported the causative agent of this disease was a new coronavirus called acute breathing syndrome 2 (SARS-CoV-2).
Since then, diseases caused by SARS-CoV-2 infection are called coronavirus disease (COVID-19).
Evidence to date suggests that about 80% of the people with COVID-19 suffer from mild disease, which is a respiratory infection with or without pneumonia, with most of the sufferer cured.
In about 14% of cases, COVID-19 develops into a more severe disease and requires hospital care, while 6% of other cases suffer from critical diseases that require intensive care.
