Corona (CoV) virus comes from the Coronaviridae family, consisting of a group of veiled RNA viruses, positive senses, and single strands.
This virus has the largest genome of 26 to 32 kilobasas between RNA viruses called "CoV", because its morphology is similar to the crown under the electron microscope.
According to its structure, the CoV has an unenhanced genome that has similar settings.
About two thirds of the genomes are two large open-read structures that overlap each other. They are transulated into polyproteins replicas of pp1a and ppp1ab.
Polyproteins have further processing to form 16 nonstructureal proteins, called nsp1~16.
The rest of the genome consists of open - read skeletons (ORF) for structural proteins, which include bulges or spikes (S), veils or envelopes (E), membranes (M), and nucleoproteins (N).
A number of specific complementary proteins for certain bloodlines are also encoded by various CoV bloodlines.
Based on differences in protein sequences, CoVs are classified into four genus (alpha-CoVs, beta-CoVs, gamma-CoVs, and delta-CoVs); among the four genus beta-CoVs have the most number of HCOVs and are divided into four bloodlines (A, B, C, and D).
Phlogenetic evidence suggests that bats and rodents are a source of genes mostly alpha-CoV and beta-CoV, while birds are the main reservoirs of gamma-CoV and delta-CoV.
For thousands of years, CoV has continued to cross species barriers and some CoVs have become important pathogens in humans.
