Updates of "expected case" diagnostic criteria and "confirmed case" COVID-19 need to be performed
On February 6, 2020, our team published quick counsel guides for diagnosis and treatment of new coronavirus infections 2019 (2019-nCoV). These guides are based on our experience and are good references to the worldwide pandemic.
Even so, coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) is a new disease, our awareness and knowledge are increasing on the basis of ongoing research findings and clinical practical experiences; therefore, diagnostic strategies and treatment are also being updated.
In this letter, we answered one of the comments on our guide and provided the latest diagnostic criteria for "insurgible cases" and "confirmed cases" based on the Diagnosis Guide and Treatment to COVID-19 (seventh version) issued by the National Health Commission of the People's Republic of China.
In December 2019, the new coronavirus 2019 (2019-nCoV) had caused an outbreak, which is now formally called coronavirus 2019 (COVID-19) and is named coronavirus of acute respiratory syndrome 2 (SARS-CoV-2).
On March 11, 2020, WHO described COVID-19 as a pandemic.
To fight SARS-CoV-2 infections, our team developed a quick guidance guide and that guide was published online at Military Medical Research on February 6, 2020.
That guide has drawn a lot of attention since it was published.
However, it is worth noting that COVID-19 is a new disease, our awareness and knowledge are increasing by ongoing research findings and clinical practical experiences; hence, diagnostic strategies and treatment are also being renewed.
For example, between January 16, 2020 and March 3, 2020, this commission has issued a total of seven editions with some contexts being changed quite a lot.
Our guide received comments from Zhou et al, they introduced a simple score-giving proposal based on their clinical experience.
Their work adds new evidence for our guidance as well as a valuable reference to this pandemic worldwide.
We support their significant work and express our gratitude.
Nevertheless, their work also requires updates based on the Diagnosis Guide and Control for the latest COVID-19 (the seventh trial version) and the latest study.
Based on the seventh edition (March 3 of 2020), to confirm the alleged case requires a combination of one of epidemiological historys with two clinical manifestations to make a comprehensive analysis, or a need for the completion of three clinical manifestations if there is no clear epidemiological history:
epidemiological history: (1) history of travel or living in the city of Wuhan and surrounding areas, or other communities where the case COVID-19 has been reported in the last 14 days before the symptoms awitan; (2) contact with cases of SARS-CoV-2 (with positive nucleic acid tests); (3) contact with patients with fever or respiratory symptoms from the city of Wuhan and surrounding areas, or other communities where the COVID-19 case has been reported in the last 14 days before the symptoms; (4) a history of contact with clustered cases of confirmed cases (1 case with fever and/or respiratory symptoms occurred in 2 weeks in small areas, like home, school class, etc.).
Clinical manifestations: (1) fever and/or respiratory symptoms; (2) imaging features COVID-19 infection; (3) total count of white blood cells indicates normal lymphocyte count, decreased, or decreased at the initial rate.
Diagnosing a confirmed case must be based on an alleged case with one of the following pathogenic or serological evidence: (1) positive PCR real-time test for SARS-CoV-2; (2) the whole sequence of viral genomes indicates high homogenity for the known new coronavirus; (3) positive for IgM antibody and IgG antibody against SARS-COV-2 in serum tests; or changes of Ig-specific Ig-CoV-2 antibody from negative to positive, or titer increases its rise in recovery at an acute rate.
We can see that PCR's real-time nucleic acid tests in a sample of the respiratory tract or blood were added to the second edition (January 18, 2020) and third (January 22, 2020).
The pathogenic detection of blood samples was added to the fourth edition (January 27, 2020) and the fifth (February 8, 2020); then serological evidence was added to the seventh edition.
These modifications are based on the ongoing research of researchers to find optimum nucleic acid detection kits for rapid diagnosis, as well as samples from the breathing channel including blood-grafting, which increases the availability of various specimens, and supports the integrating of certain antibody positives into the confirmed criteria.
In addition, there is increasing evidence that reminds us to be alert to patients with animative symptoms and without symptoms.
Therefore, the Zhou et al flow chart must be renewed because they classify people without clinical symptoms as "low risk".
The score system also needs to be verified in future clinical practices and studies.
In closing, we expect more direct evidence to appear and ask the reader to comment.
For the diagnosis of "surprised cases" and "confirmed cases", we suggest that we follow and comply with the latest guidelines in each country.
Our team will also update our guidelines periodically as help.
